, 44, 45]]}, {"review_id": "HkeQCAq6hQ", "rebuttal_id": "B1xZ6uCaT7", "sentence_index": 13, "text": "The three references and the follow-up work that you cite give different methods for obtaining a certificate-of-guarantee that a datapoint is robust in a fixed epsilon l_\\infty ball, with varying levels of scalability/generality/ease-of-implementation.", "coarse": "concur", "fine": "rebuttal_answer", "alignment": ["context_sentences", [33, 34, 35, 37, 38, 39, 40, 41, 42, 43, 44, 45]]}, {"review_id": "HkeQCAq6hQ", "rebuttal_id": "B1xZ6uCaT7", "sentence_index": 14, "text": "For those datapoints where they can produce such a certificate", "coarse": "concur", "fine": "rebuttal_answer", "alignment": ["context_sentences", [33, 34, 35, 37, 38, 39, 40, 41, 42, 43, 44, 45]]}, {"review_id": "HkeQCAq6hQ", "rebuttal_id": "B1xZ6uCaT7", "sentence_index": 15, "text": ", the minimal adversarial distortion is lower-bounded by that fixed epsilon.", "coarse": "concur", "fine": "rebuttal_answer", "alignment": ["context_sentences", [33, 34, 35, 37, 38, 39, 40, 41, 42, 43, 44, 45]]}, {"review_id": "HkeQCAq6hQ", "rebuttal_id": "B1xZ6uCaT7", "sentence_index": 16, "text": "This is important work to be sure, but we view it as predominantly orthogonal to ours, for which we define robustness differently, as the \u201cvolume\u201d of adversarial examples rather than the distance to a single adversarial example.", "coarse": "dispute", "fine": "rebuttal_mitigate-criticism", "alignment": ["context_sentences", [33, 34, 35, 37, 38, 39, 40, 41, 42, 43, 44, 45]]}, {"review_id": "HkeQCAq6hQ", "rebuttal_id": "B1xZ6uCaT7", "sentence_index": 17, "text": "We actively argue that the minimal adversarial distortion is not a reliable measure of neural network robustness in many scenarios, as it is dictated by the position of a single violation, and conveys nothing about the amount of violations present.", "coarse": "dispute", "fine": "rebuttal_reject-criticism", "alignment": ["context_sentences", [33, 34, 35, 